│ ## Initial Observations ##                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ The reproducer is already minimized. Based on my experience in debugging    │
│ these bugs, the issue is likely introduced by the *first transformation*,   │
│ or due to incorrect analysis information feeding into it.                   │
│ Here, the *first transformation* means the *first transformation point*     │
│ that modifies the IR in the pass regardless of whether it's in the          │
│ `autofix/build/llvm-build/111874/bin/opt -p loop-vectorize -S               │
│ /tmp/reprod_nxh2jer9.l` module or other modules.                            │
│ #### Opt Information ####                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ To gather more insight, I ran `opt` to inspect both the transformations and │
│ the analysis results. Below are the command and the resulting log:          │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ $ bin/opt -p loop-vectorize -S --debug-only= /tmp/reprod_nxh2jer9.ll        │
│ opt: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:7435:                  │
│ llvm::VectorizationFactor llvm::LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF():  │
│ Assertion `(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||                           │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width),         │
│ CostCtx, OrigLoop)) && " VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed"' │
│ failed.                                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ From this log, I identified the first transformation point as:              │
│                                                                             │
